1
00:00:03,881 --> 00:00:04,881
Hey!

2
00:00:04,961 --> 00:00:06,081
SHIREEN: Hey.

3
00:00:06,201 --> 00:00:07,841
-So, Felicity...
-FELICITY: Hi.

4
00:00:08,001 --> 00:00:09,001
-Harry.
-Hello.

5
00:00:09,081 --> 00:00:10,601
-Pavel. And Paul.
-Hi.

6
00:00:11,001 --> 00:00:13,881
Everyone, this is Bill,
your new housemate.

7
00:00:14,041 --> 00:00:16,121
-Be nice.
-(ALL LAUGHING)

8
00:00:17,721 --> 00:00:18,721
Six bedrooms?

9
00:00:18,841 --> 00:00:21,441
I've got audio equipment,
so some extra space would be good.

10
00:00:21,881 --> 00:00:23,001
I'd quite like underfloor heating.

11
00:00:31,681 --> 00:00:32,681
ESTATE AGENT: This is bedroom five.

12
00:00:32,761 --> 00:00:34,361
It hasn't got a door.

13
00:00:34,841 --> 00:00:37,361
Er, bedroom six is just through there.

14
00:00:40,441 --> 00:00:44,481
As you can see, this offers more space.

15
00:00:50,361 --> 00:00:52,641
(HORNS BLARING)

16
00:00:56,761 --> 00:00:58,041
What do other people do?

17
00:00:59,481 --> 00:01:01,521
-Other people have money.
-MAN: Forgive me, but...

18
00:01:02,801 --> 00:01:04,641
Are you looking for somewhere to live?

19
00:01:08,241 --> 00:01:09,561
FELICITY: Oh, wow!

20
00:01:10,441 --> 00:01:12,361
-(ALL EXCLAIMING)
-PAUL: Oh, mate, check the tower!

21
00:01:12,441 --> 00:01:14,881
LANDLORD: (STAMMERING)
I'm afraid the tower is unsafe.

22
00:01:16,721 --> 00:01:18,001
Bill, look at it!

23
00:01:19,161 --> 00:01:21,681
Yeah, but why is it so cheap?

24
00:01:21,841 --> 00:01:24,601
This place is great. The rooms are huge!

25
00:01:25,201 --> 00:01:27,641
Can I move in tonight?
My hosts are kicking me out.

26
00:01:27,921 --> 00:01:31,121
Yes. Yes, of course.
So, you'll sign the contract?

27
00:01:31,321 --> 00:01:32,641
-ALL: Yes!
-Yeah, of course!

28
00:01:35,761 --> 00:01:36,761
Bill?

29
00:01:46,401 --> 00:01:47,481
(THUNDER CRASHING)

30
00:01:56,401 --> 00:01:57,561
(FLOORBOARD CREAKS)

31
00:02:00,801 --> 00:02:01,841
(CHUCKLES SOFTLY)

32
00:02:03,121 --> 00:02:04,241
Wicked.

33
00:02:16,281 --> 00:02:17,761
(CREAKING IN DISTANCE)

34
00:02:27,041 --> 00:02:28,641
(WIND BLOWING)

35
00:02:31,961 --> 00:02:33,081
(BLOWS)

36
00:02:36,961 --> 00:02:38,161
(VIOLIN MUSIC PLAYING)

37
00:02:41,561 --> 00:02:43,121
(CREAKING IN DISTANCE)

38
00:02:50,841 --> 00:02:52,281
(CREAKING CONTINUES)

39
00:02:54,881 --> 00:02:56,481
(THUNDER CRASHING)

40
00:03:04,961 --> 00:03:07,041
PAVEL: What? No, no.
No, no. Stop!

41
00:03:07,521 --> 00:03:08,681
-(RECORD SCRATCHES)
-Stop!

42
00:03:08,761 --> 00:03:10,361
-(MUSIC CONTINUES)
-(PAVEL SCREAMING)

43
00:03:15,001 --> 00:03:16,921
(THEME MUSIC PLAYING)

44
00:04:03,641 --> 00:04:06,321
Three... Two...

45
00:04:06,801 --> 00:04:07,801
(TARDIS MATERIALISING)

46
00:04:07,881 --> 00:04:08,881
One.

47
00:04:12,881 --> 00:04:14,081
(CHUCKLES)

48
00:04:16,761 --> 00:04:18,041
That's all you've got?

49
00:04:19,441 --> 00:04:20,881
I thought you'd have loads.

50
00:04:20,961 --> 00:04:22,241
Thanks for helping, yeah?

51
00:04:27,001 --> 00:04:28,481
You should hire this out.

52
00:04:29,761 --> 00:04:31,281
Like a removal service.

53
00:04:31,361 --> 00:04:34,601
Removals? Bill, I'm a Time Lord.

54
00:04:35,321 --> 00:04:37,561
-"Time Lord"? What's that? Your job?
-No, it's my, er...

55
00:04:38,801 --> 00:04:40,241
People. My species.

56
00:04:40,481 --> 00:04:43,201
Doesn't sound like a species.
Sounds posh, like...

57
00:04:43,801 --> 00:04:45,441
"Yes, my lord." Doff my cap.

58
00:04:45,561 --> 00:04:47,441
Oh, well, that's why I gave it up.
Ran away.

59
00:04:47,521 --> 00:04:50,521
(CHUCKLES) Time Lords. That's hilarious.

60
00:04:51,161 --> 00:04:52,481
Do you wear robes and big hats?

61
00:04:52,601 --> 00:04:54,681
No, er, big collars mostly.

62
00:04:56,281 --> 00:04:57,841
-Do you want the postcode?
-Sorry?

63
00:04:58,321 --> 00:04:59,321
To find the house.

64
00:05:00,481 --> 00:05:04,761
Bill, the TARDIS uses multi-dimensional
space-time coordinates.

65
00:05:05,441 --> 00:05:06,481
So you know where it is?

66
00:05:07,441 --> 00:05:09,441
Okay, right, put the postcode in here.

67
00:05:12,121 --> 00:05:15,001
-I saw the bedroom. Do you sleep here?
-If I need to.

68
00:05:15,961 --> 00:05:17,081
-Done?
-Yeah.

69
00:05:17,601 --> 00:05:19,881
"If I need to." What does that mean?

70
00:05:19,961 --> 00:05:22,241
-Sleep's for tortoises.
-Not "Time Lords"?

71
00:05:22,401 --> 00:05:25,361
No. Unless we've regenerated,
or had a big lunch.

72
00:05:25,721 --> 00:05:27,041
Regenerated?

73
00:05:28,761 --> 00:05:31,201
Oh, the questions.
The questions, the questions.

74
00:05:31,321 --> 00:05:33,681
Just remember "Time Lords."”
That's enough for now.

75
00:05:34,081 --> 00:05:36,441
-Oh, here we are.
-Ah!

76
00:05:37,201 --> 00:05:38,881
(BIRDS CHIRPING)

77
00:05:41,841 --> 00:05:43,001
(DOCTOR GRUNTS)

78
00:05:44,001 --> 00:05:46,441
Oh, I'll use the TARDIS.
Take it all to your room.

79
00:05:46,521 --> 00:05:48,801
Firstly, I don't know
which one my room is.

80
00:05:48,921 --> 00:05:51,641
And secondly, that's weird.
And I want to make a good impression.

81
00:05:53,681 --> 00:05:56,281
It's cool. I'll just get everything
out of the TARDIS and then you can go.

82
00:05:57,041 --> 00:05:59,361
Thanks for the lift, though. Bye.

83
00:05:59,681 --> 00:06:01,241
(TREES CREAKING)

84
00:06:03,601 --> 00:06:04,761
That's your house?

85
00:06:05,241 --> 00:06:07,081
Sharing, yeah. Six of us. Renting.

86
00:06:08,921 --> 00:06:10,401
I thought you were students.

87
00:06:10,521 --> 00:06:12,281
Yeah. I was like, "What's the catch?"

88
00:06:12,401 --> 00:06:14,801
But actually, it's fine.
Just a bit draughty.

89
00:06:17,081 --> 00:06:18,241
Draughty?

90
00:06:21,161 --> 00:06:22,401
(CREAKING CONTINUES)

91
00:06:29,201 --> 00:06:30,241
I meant draughty inside.

92
00:06:32,081 --> 00:06:34,561
Interesting. I'll help you in.

93
00:06:34,641 --> 00:06:35,641
No, no. No, it's fine.

94
00:06:35,721 --> 00:06:37,241
You really don't have to. It's like...

95
00:06:37,361 --> 00:06:38,721
-Really not a problem.
-No, wait, honestly.

96
00:06:38,801 --> 00:06:40,321
Um, if you just...

97
00:06:41,041 --> 00:06:43,121
If you can just go
and do history or whatever.

98
00:06:44,001 --> 00:06:45,001
(SIGHS)

99
00:06:45,521 --> 00:06:48,641
Hey! Where have you been? I thought...
Ah! You're the Doctor?

100
00:06:48,721 --> 00:06:49,961
Yes, hi. Can I get past?

101
00:06:50,041 --> 00:06:51,521
Oh, yeah. He's just helping

102
00:06:51,601 --> 00:06:52,801
-with the move.
-Helping?

103
00:06:52,881 --> 00:06:53,921
-He's just my...
-DOCTOR: Friend.

104
00:06:54,001 --> 00:06:56,241
-Granddad.
-Wait, I don't look old enough...

105
00:06:56,481 --> 00:07:00,801
To hold that box for very long.

106
00:07:00,881 --> 00:07:03,761
There. (SIGHS) Me.

107
00:07:04,001 --> 00:07:06,121
How exciting is this?

108
00:07:06,201 --> 00:07:07,961
Oh, wow! Doctor! Legend!

109
00:07:09,281 --> 00:07:12,241
-He's my granddad.
-Oh, come on.

110
00:07:12,561 --> 00:07:14,201
Father, at least, please.

111
00:07:14,321 --> 00:07:17,481
All right. Grandfather. (LAUGHS)

112
00:07:18,841 --> 00:07:20,161
You really can go now, though.

113
00:07:22,041 --> 00:07:24,081
Thanks for the help. Job done.

114
00:07:26,001 --> 00:07:28,081
Okay. Bye.

115
00:07:31,001 --> 00:07:32,081
Bye.

116
00:07:36,081 --> 00:07:39,201
He's your granddad? That's awesome.
Mine went greypacking

117
00:07:39,281 --> 00:07:40,921
on the Great Wall of China
with his boyfriend,

118
00:07:41,281 --> 00:07:42,561
but they got arrested
for trying to steal a bit.

119
00:07:43,201 --> 00:07:44,561
-A bit of what?
-Of the wall.

120
00:07:45,521 --> 00:07:46,521
Okay.

121
00:07:46,961 --> 00:07:49,281
-You want a hand?
-Er, yeah.

122
00:07:50,641 --> 00:07:52,881
-(INDISTINCT CHATTER)
-Thanks.

123
00:07:58,801 --> 00:08:00,481
Keep thinking there's gonna be
one of those bookcases

124
00:08:00,561 --> 00:08:01,801
that you pull special books,

125
00:08:02,041 --> 00:08:03,761
-and it's a secret passage.
-Yeah?

126
00:08:04,081 --> 00:08:06,041
-Spooky.
-(SIGHS)

127
00:08:09,321 --> 00:08:11,241
(MUFFLED VIOLIN MUSIC PLAYING)

128
00:08:11,441 --> 00:08:12,441
Thanks.

129
00:08:16,881 --> 00:08:18,241
Met Pavel on my first day.

130
00:08:18,921 --> 00:08:21,321
Often does this.
Sits in his room for days.

131
00:08:21,401 --> 00:08:23,001
Says it gets him in the zone.

132
00:08:23,121 --> 00:08:25,841
-(LAUGHING)
-All these lot are empty.

133
00:08:30,161 --> 00:08:31,441
PAUL: Yeah, this is nice.

134
00:08:31,761 --> 00:08:33,761
I picked my room
before I'd even seen up here.

135
00:08:34,801 --> 00:08:36,001
BILL: Thought you wanted the tower.

136
00:08:36,081 --> 00:08:38,281
PAUL: Yeah, I wish. Can't find a way in.

137
00:08:39,761 --> 00:08:41,521
There's a freshers' party
in the park tonight.

138
00:08:42,641 --> 00:08:44,961
This lot aren't interested,
but could be fun.

139
00:08:47,961 --> 00:08:49,041
Or not. Er...

140
00:08:49,161 --> 00:08:52,561
But either way, I was saying
we should throw our own party, you know.

141
00:08:53,521 --> 00:08:56,521
Pop up. Freestyle. Boom!

142
00:08:57,241 --> 00:08:59,001
(CHUCKLES) Yeah, sounds good.

143
00:09:05,841 --> 00:09:07,121
-See you later, then.
-Sure.

144
00:09:09,841 --> 00:09:10,841
(DOOR CLOSES)

145
00:09:13,521 --> 00:09:15,801
Here you go, Mum. My own place.

146
00:09:16,721 --> 00:09:18,121
You proud?

147
00:09:20,041 --> 00:09:21,041
Thanks.

148
00:09:27,721 --> 00:09:28,761
(CREAKING)

149
00:09:29,241 --> 00:09:32,241
(LAUGHS, MIMICS CREAKING)

150
00:09:35,041 --> 00:09:36,321
(CREAKING)

151
00:09:40,081 --> 00:09:41,321
Stop it.

152
00:09:41,681 --> 00:09:44,881
There's no living puddles or...

153
00:09:45,841 --> 00:09:47,841
Weird robots, big fish.

154
00:09:48,081 --> 00:09:50,001
It's just a new house.

155
00:09:51,441 --> 00:09:53,281
And people you don't know.

156
00:09:54,481 --> 00:09:55,601
Not scary at all.

157
00:10:01,041 --> 00:10:02,921
(CREAKING)

158
00:10:05,561 --> 00:10:06,561
(THUNDER CRASHES)

159
00:10:12,521 --> 00:10:14,721
(SIGHS) I always get nervous
when there's no reception,

160
00:10:15,201 --> 00:10:16,641
like something bad's going to happen.

161
00:10:16,721 --> 00:10:20,161
-We'll have to get a landline.
-Landline? What is this, Scotland?

162
00:10:20,481 --> 00:10:21,921
-(LAUGHS)
-HARRY: Actually,

163
00:10:22,001 --> 00:10:24,881
I was unpacking just now
and heard this... Tapping?

164
00:10:25,121 --> 00:10:26,121
Little footsteps?

165
00:10:26,201 --> 00:10:28,081
-Like, in the room above.
-What?

166
00:10:28,361 --> 00:10:29,841
BOTH: Ooh...

167
00:10:30,521 --> 00:10:32,521
Maybe it's a little doll
who's come to life.

168
00:10:32,601 --> 00:10:35,641
-Or maybe a massive, freaky spider.
-(SCOFFS)

169
00:10:35,881 --> 00:10:38,921
-Probably just a mouse.
-Yeah, we know. Just messing with her.

170
00:10:39,001 --> 00:10:40,521
Mice. If there's mice, I'm leaving.

171
00:10:41,361 --> 00:10:42,801
(SCRATCHING)

172
00:10:43,481 --> 00:10:44,521
What's that?

173
00:10:45,481 --> 00:10:47,081
-Pavel?
-Pavel's upstairs.

174
00:10:48,241 --> 00:10:49,521
(SCRATCHING)

175
00:10:50,521 --> 00:10:52,761
-Paul, go and have a look.
-Why me?

176
00:10:53,001 --> 00:10:54,041
You're physically the biggest.

177
00:10:54,161 --> 00:10:55,441
(LAUGHS) And the most expendable.

178
00:10:56,081 --> 00:10:57,721
(THUMPING)

179
00:10:58,841 --> 00:11:00,401
It's in the kitchen.

180
00:11:02,161 --> 00:11:03,401
It's all right. I'll go.

181
00:11:14,601 --> 00:11:16,041
(THUMPING)

182
00:11:22,641 --> 00:11:24,721
-(THUMPING)
-(GASPS)

183
00:11:25,201 --> 00:11:27,601
-(THUMPING)
-Maybe it's just the central heating.

184
00:11:35,281 --> 00:11:37,681
-(CLANGING)
-(ALL SIGHING)

185
00:11:37,841 --> 00:11:38,881
(SONIC SCREWDRIVER BUZZING)

186
00:11:38,961 --> 00:11:40,801
-There isn't any.
-I thought...

187
00:11:40,881 --> 00:11:42,201
He'd gone home. Me, too.

188
00:11:42,681 --> 00:11:43,801
Isn't any what?

189
00:11:43,921 --> 00:11:45,201
Central heating.

190
00:11:45,321 --> 00:11:47,401
I've been looking around,
inside and out.

191
00:11:47,481 --> 00:11:49,321
Very interesting. Lots of wood.

192
00:11:49,401 --> 00:11:50,801
Er, why are you still here?

193
00:11:52,081 --> 00:11:53,361
Do you know what that is?

194
00:11:53,881 --> 00:11:56,961
That's an oil-burning heater.
You might need it.

195
00:11:57,721 --> 00:12:01,201
There's no washing machine either.
The hob is from the '30s.

196
00:12:01,321 --> 00:12:02,361
-Thanks so much.
-The power sockets

197
00:12:02,441 --> 00:12:04,321
will not take your devices.

198
00:12:04,401 --> 00:12:05,721
Oh, I thought it was just my room.

199
00:12:05,841 --> 00:12:07,561
No, no, no. They are out of date.

200
00:12:09,401 --> 00:12:11,641
What's that smell?

201
00:12:12,921 --> 00:12:15,881
-Is that Chinese food? I love Chinese.
-Doctor!

202
00:12:18,161 --> 00:12:21,041
There might be a few old things,

203
00:12:21,161 --> 00:12:22,881
but it just needs updating.

204
00:12:22,961 --> 00:12:24,841
It's not like there's some
massive mystery going on.

205
00:12:25,201 --> 00:12:27,641
Did you hear the trees creaking
outside when we arrived?

206
00:12:28,401 --> 00:12:29,561
Yeah, it was the wind.

207
00:12:30,001 --> 00:12:31,241
There wasn't any wind.

208
00:12:33,841 --> 00:12:35,001
You should find another house.

209
00:12:35,401 --> 00:12:37,001
I don't think so.

210
00:12:37,401 --> 00:12:38,601
The rooms are really big.

211
00:12:38,681 --> 00:12:40,561
Exactly, and it's still the best place
for the money.

212
00:12:40,881 --> 00:12:42,761
I'll just call the landlord
and sort it out.

213
00:12:42,841 --> 00:12:44,241
(SIGHS) You can't. No reception.

214
00:12:44,401 --> 00:12:46,801
-Okay, so I'll go down the hill... Oh.
-(CREAKING)

215
00:12:47,801 --> 00:12:49,001
Aye.

216
00:12:51,801 --> 00:12:52,881
Didn't hear you come in.

217
00:12:53,801 --> 00:12:56,561
For a man such as myself,
discretion is second nature.

218
00:12:56,921 --> 00:12:59,001
So, a gathering. You're all here.

219
00:12:59,441 --> 00:13:00,881
No, except one...

220
00:13:01,201 --> 00:13:04,081
-Pavel's upstairs.
-LANDLORD: And one in addition.

221
00:13:04,401 --> 00:13:05,401
He's the Doctor.

222
00:13:05,681 --> 00:13:09,201
-Doctor?
-Oh, he's... He's my grandfather.

223
00:13:09,321 --> 00:13:12,361
-What, assisting with the relocation?
-That's right, yeah.

224
00:13:12,441 --> 00:13:14,241
It's a heart-breaking experience,

225
00:13:14,321 --> 00:13:17,161
to leave one's charge behind
all alone in the big wide world.

226
00:13:17,241 --> 00:13:18,281
Indeed, yes.

227
00:13:19,761 --> 00:13:20,761
You got children?

228
00:13:21,081 --> 00:13:23,001
I... Yes. A daughter.

229
00:13:23,121 --> 00:13:25,521
But I'm most fortunate
she's still under my protection.

230
00:13:25,681 --> 00:13:27,761
So long as that's the case,
I'm most content.

231
00:13:28,921 --> 00:13:32,441
So, now, I was calling to see
if everything's satisfactory.

232
00:13:33,041 --> 00:13:34,521
Actually, there are a few things.

233
00:13:35,121 --> 00:13:36,121
Yes, I see. Go on.

234
00:13:36,521 --> 00:13:37,841
-No central heating.
-Power sockets are wrong.

235
00:13:38,001 --> 00:13:39,281
-And a landline.
-Some new furniture.

236
00:13:39,401 --> 00:13:40,401
(ALL TALKING OVER EACH OTHER)

237
00:13:40,601 --> 00:13:42,321
-FELICITY: ...curtains, carpets.
-Have you got a cat?

238
00:13:42,481 --> 00:13:43,761
(CRUNCHING LOUDLY)

239
00:13:46,841 --> 00:13:48,241
(CRUNCHING QUIETLY)

240
00:13:51,081 --> 00:13:52,081
A cat?

241
00:13:55,161 --> 00:13:56,321
(STAMMERING) Er, yeah.

242
00:13:56,401 --> 00:13:58,201
Harry said that he heard
some noise upstairs,

243
00:13:58,281 --> 00:13:59,601
like walking around.

244
00:14:01,001 --> 00:14:03,561
No cats. No pets.

245
00:14:04,561 --> 00:14:07,441
You understand I won't be able
to do any of this tonight,

246
00:14:07,561 --> 00:14:09,521
but as soon as possible, yes.

247
00:14:10,601 --> 00:14:12,041
Knock on wood, do what I can.

248
00:14:12,121 --> 00:14:14,801
That's another thing.
The house is really creaky.

249
00:14:14,921 --> 00:14:16,681
Everything you touch, it's like...
(MIMICS CREAKING)

250
00:14:16,761 --> 00:14:18,321
It's unavoidable, my dear.

251
00:14:18,481 --> 00:14:20,681
-How do you get into the tower?
-You don't.

252
00:14:22,961 --> 00:14:26,801
The tower is specifically excluded
from the terms of our agreement.

253
00:14:28,201 --> 00:14:30,281
Oh, right. Well, thank you.

254
00:14:30,921 --> 00:14:32,201
No tower. Got it.

255
00:14:32,281 --> 00:14:33,481
Right.

256
00:14:38,041 --> 00:14:40,561
-Oh, er, are you staying here tonight?
-Yeah.

257
00:14:40,761 --> 00:14:41,761
Er, no, he's not.

258
00:14:41,881 --> 00:14:43,761
DOCTOR: Well, I'm not sure.
BILL: There's no reason to.

259
00:14:43,921 --> 00:14:46,441
- I probably will.
-There isn't a bed, so...

260
00:14:47,401 --> 00:14:48,561
(CHUCKLES) All right.

261
00:14:49,721 --> 00:14:51,601
Sorry, excuse me. Sorry, sorry, sorry.

262
00:14:52,921 --> 00:14:55,481
Who, um... Who's the prime minister?

263
00:14:57,401 --> 00:14:58,801
(STAMMERING) I beg your pardon?

264
00:14:59,121 --> 00:15:01,241
-Margaret Thatcher, Harriet Jones?
-(CHUCKLES) Oh, come on.

265
00:15:01,361 --> 00:15:02,361
Wilson? Eden?

266
00:15:03,801 --> 00:15:06,801
I think it's better to leave your
granddaughter here with her friends.

267
00:15:06,881 --> 00:15:10,641
They seem respectable.
And I'll keep an eye, of course.

268
00:15:17,201 --> 00:15:18,961
I'll attend to your requirements
in the morning.

269
00:15:19,041 --> 00:15:21,041
In the meantime, sleep well.

270
00:15:21,161 --> 00:15:22,641
(TUNING FORK VIBRATES)

271
00:15:30,321 --> 00:15:34,001
I take it back. You're fine. He's weird.

272
00:15:34,081 --> 00:15:36,081
(GASPS) Ah, the washing machine.

273
00:15:39,721 --> 00:15:41,641
(THUNDER CRASHING)

274
00:15:43,201 --> 00:15:44,841
That's weird.

275
00:15:47,921 --> 00:15:49,201
He's not there.

276
00:15:50,401 --> 00:15:51,841
(RUSTLING UPSTAIRS)

277
00:15:51,921 --> 00:15:54,801
That's it. That's the noise I heard.

278
00:15:55,521 --> 00:15:56,641
Fascinating.

279
00:15:59,921 --> 00:16:01,041
(RUSTLING CONTINUES)

280
00:16:06,081 --> 00:16:08,521
It's just pipes. I'm going to bed.

281
00:16:08,721 --> 00:16:10,081
BILL: Yeah, I might go up as well.

282
00:16:10,161 --> 00:16:11,921
SHIREEN: Me, too.
Locking my door though.

283
00:16:12,241 --> 00:16:13,521
Er, Grandfather?

284
00:16:15,881 --> 00:16:18,161
Hello? Yeah.

285
00:16:18,281 --> 00:16:20,401
-Perhaps you'd leave now?
-No, I'm fine.

286
00:16:20,561 --> 00:16:23,761
Well, at least, erm, go and sleep.

287
00:16:23,841 --> 00:16:25,601
Outside, in the car.

288
00:16:25,681 --> 00:16:27,841
-Are you two tired?
-Well, I...

289
00:16:27,921 --> 00:16:29,361
Good. No, I'm gonna hang about
with Simon.

290
00:16:29,441 --> 00:16:31,001
-BILL: Harry. Felicity.
-Florence.

291
00:16:31,361 --> 00:16:33,521
-Yeah, why?
-Well, we're gonna chill. Yeah?

292
00:16:33,601 --> 00:16:34,881
Yeah. Okay, yes!

293
00:16:34,961 --> 00:16:36,961
-Put some tunes on, yes?
-Yes!

294
00:16:37,041 --> 00:16:38,561
-HARRY: All right.
-I'm good at making friends.

295
00:16:38,641 --> 00:16:40,401
-Give me your phone.
-But why? There's no reception.

296
00:16:40,561 --> 00:16:41,601
Phone.

297
00:16:44,881 --> 00:16:46,961
(POP SONG PLAYING)

298
00:16:47,601 --> 00:16:49,841
-HARRY: I love this.
-Do you know who this is?

299
00:16:49,921 --> 00:16:53,121
Do I know who this is?
Yes, I know who this is.

300
00:16:53,201 --> 00:16:56,001
Yeah, it's Spotify,
so it's probably random.

301
00:16:57,001 --> 00:16:58,641
-Mix...
-You like Little Mix?

302
00:16:58,761 --> 00:17:01,601
Oh, clearly she does.
Look, there's a whole playlist here.

303
00:17:01,681 --> 00:17:03,481
-What else have you got on this?
-Can I have a word, please?

304
00:17:08,241 --> 00:17:10,641
Honestly, Doctor,
there's nothing going on.

305
00:17:11,281 --> 00:17:13,761
Nothing weird, nothing alien.

306
00:17:13,841 --> 00:17:18,321
Just an old house and a dodgy landlord,
which is pretty standard for students.

307
00:17:19,681 --> 00:17:22,561
I'll see you later
for more exciting TARDIS action,

308
00:17:22,641 --> 00:17:25,681
but basically, this is the bit
of my life that you're not in.

309
00:17:27,361 --> 00:17:28,361
Do you know what I mean?

310
00:17:29,201 --> 00:17:30,961
-I know what you mean.
-Thanks.

311
00:17:32,281 --> 00:17:34,841
So, up the wooden hill you go.

312
00:17:35,761 --> 00:17:37,121
-Sleep well.
-Okay.

313
00:17:37,201 --> 00:17:38,961
Maybe, before you do,
you should check on your friend

314
00:17:39,041 --> 00:17:40,561
who hasn't been seen for a day

315
00:17:40,641 --> 00:17:42,721
and who has strange music
coming out of his room.

316
00:17:42,801 --> 00:17:45,521
-They say he just does that.
-Nobody just does anything.

317
00:17:47,121 --> 00:17:49,361
-You're not leaving, are you?
-No.

318
00:17:50,761 --> 00:17:52,041
Your friend will probably be fine.

319
00:17:52,401 --> 00:17:54,241
-(KNOCKS)
-Knock on wood.

320
00:17:55,441 --> 00:17:57,761
We need to have a talk
about your taste in music.

321
00:17:57,841 --> 00:17:59,281
You comin' up?

322
00:17:59,361 --> 00:18:00,521
Yeah.

323
00:18:02,481 --> 00:18:04,241
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

324
00:18:06,121 --> 00:18:07,601
(RUSTLING)

325
00:18:10,161 --> 00:18:13,441
-(DOOR CREAKING)
-Oh, this freaky Scooby Doo house!

326
00:18:13,521 --> 00:18:17,521
-Er, well... (CLEARS THROAT)
-Ooh...

327
00:18:17,601 --> 00:18:20,001
If you get scared in the night,
you know where I am. Yeah?

328
00:18:20,081 --> 00:18:23,601
-What?
-Just if you need any of my help,

329
00:18:23,681 --> 00:18:25,881
-or whatever, you know?
-Yeah, erm...

330
00:18:27,281 --> 00:18:30,001
I get that you're into me, but, erm...

331
00:18:30,961 --> 00:18:32,841
Sorry, you're not my type.

332
00:18:33,681 --> 00:18:35,921
Just, erm, I tend to go for girls,
usually, so...

333
00:18:36,241 --> 00:18:38,161
Oh... Oh, right!

334
00:18:38,281 --> 00:18:40,281
-I was never in with a chance. Awesome.
-(LAUGHS)

335
00:18:40,721 --> 00:18:43,041
-(FLOOR CREAKING)
-Jeez, stop!

336
00:18:43,121 --> 00:18:45,961
-This is what I'm talking about.
-(CREAKING)

337
00:18:46,041 --> 00:18:47,321
This stuff really freaks you out,
doesn't it?

338
00:18:47,401 --> 00:18:49,681
No! It's just annoying.

339
00:18:49,761 --> 00:18:51,041
-Oh.
-SHIREEN: Go to bed!

340
00:18:51,121 --> 00:18:52,161
Sure.

341
00:18:53,201 --> 00:18:54,601
(DOOR CREAKING)

342
00:18:55,361 --> 00:18:57,481
-(FLOORBOARD CREAKING REPEATEDLY)
-(THUNDER RUMBLING)

343
00:18:58,601 --> 00:19:00,921
See you in the morning.
(MIMICS CHOKING)

344
00:19:01,001 --> 00:19:02,001
Night, then.

345
00:19:03,721 --> 00:19:05,841
Why didn't you get a room next to me,
like we said?

346
00:19:05,921 --> 00:19:07,761
What? I dunno.

347
00:19:08,321 --> 00:19:11,241
-Doesn't mean anything.
-I'm not cool enough, is that it?

348
00:19:11,561 --> 00:19:13,921
No! Shut up! These are my mates, too.

349
00:19:14,001 --> 00:19:16,241
-(PAUL MAKING GHOST NOISES)
-Paul, not funny.

350
00:19:17,481 --> 00:19:18,801
Do you fancy him?

351
00:19:18,921 --> 00:19:20,321
No, who? Paul? Why? No.

352
00:19:20,401 --> 00:19:23,601
-(PAUL SCREAMING)
-Hey, it's not funny!

353
00:19:23,881 --> 00:19:26,481
-(CRASHING)
-(PAUL SCREAMING)

354
00:19:29,481 --> 00:19:30,641
Paul?

355
00:19:33,681 --> 00:19:34,961
Are you okay?

356
00:19:35,081 --> 00:19:36,081
Mate?

357
00:19:36,561 --> 00:19:38,281
Come on, we got the joke.

358
00:19:40,521 --> 00:19:42,641
-(KNOCKING)
-(BOTH GASP)

359
00:19:42,761 --> 00:19:45,601
-(CHUCKLES) ALI right.
-See?

360
00:19:45,681 --> 00:19:49,161
He's fine. Okay. See you in the morning.

361
00:19:49,921 --> 00:19:51,201
(KNOCKING)

362
00:19:51,281 --> 00:19:52,961
-What?
-(KNOCKING CONTINUES)

363
00:19:53,201 --> 00:19:54,481
Er, what's going on?

364
00:19:55,121 --> 00:19:57,601
(KNOCKING CONTINUES
FROM MULTIPLE DIRECTIONS)

365
00:19:57,681 --> 00:19:58,721
Paul?

366
00:19:59,361 --> 00:20:01,041
-(KNOCKING)
-(DOOR RATTLING)

367
00:20:01,361 --> 00:20:02,481
Ah, we should get the Doctor.

368
00:20:02,601 --> 00:20:04,641
Why? What's he gonna do? Lecture?

369
00:20:05,481 --> 00:20:06,801
(BOTH GASP)

370
00:20:06,921 --> 00:20:10,241
-Just a normal day. Just a normal day...
-(BOTH GASP)

371
00:20:11,121 --> 00:20:12,121
Up.

372
00:20:17,441 --> 00:20:18,481
(POP MUSIC PLAYING)

373
00:20:18,561 --> 00:20:19,841
Do you like this music, Doctor?

374
00:20:19,921 --> 00:20:22,121
Reminds me of Quincy Jones.

375
00:20:23,201 --> 00:20:24,881
I stepped in for him once.

376
00:20:25,681 --> 00:20:28,961
The bassist he'd hired turned out to be
a Klarj neon death voc bot.

377
00:20:29,041 --> 00:20:31,281
What was worse, he couldn't play.

378
00:20:31,921 --> 00:20:33,281
This is very interesting.

379
00:20:34,121 --> 00:20:35,761
-The door?
-Because it isn't.

380
00:20:35,841 --> 00:20:38,401
-Isn't...
-A door. Any more.

381
00:20:38,481 --> 00:20:39,681
Try to open it.

382
00:20:41,921 --> 00:20:43,761
-(RATTLING)
-Come on.

383
00:20:43,841 --> 00:20:45,601
Shireen did it a minute ago.

384
00:20:46,801 --> 00:20:48,721
-So, it's locked?
-No. Look.

385
00:20:49,961 --> 00:20:51,281
DOCTOR: It's completely sealed.

386
00:20:52,161 --> 00:20:53,361
FELICITY: I don't understand.

387
00:20:53,801 --> 00:20:56,321
(RATTLING, BANGING)

388
00:21:03,241 --> 00:21:05,521
-The shutters!
-What about them?

389
00:21:05,601 --> 00:21:06,801
Closed by themselves.

390
00:21:13,521 --> 00:21:14,881
Sealed.

391
00:21:14,961 --> 00:21:16,561
So, we're trapped.

392
00:21:16,641 --> 00:21:18,161
Maybe that's the idea.

393
00:21:18,321 --> 00:21:20,481
-What do you mean?
-(RUSTLING)

394
00:21:20,561 --> 00:21:21,921
What's that?

395
00:21:22,761 --> 00:21:24,881
-(LOUD CREAKING)
-No, no, no. There's something in here.

396
00:21:25,601 --> 00:21:27,721
-I can't be trapped! I can't!
-Wait!

397
00:21:30,281 --> 00:21:31,361
(BANGING)

398
00:21:32,881 --> 00:21:33,881
(GASPING)

399
00:21:37,361 --> 00:21:39,241
-Don't go out there!
-I can't be trapped!

400
00:21:43,241 --> 00:21:46,281
Great. Now we're stuck here.

401
00:21:46,761 --> 00:21:48,161
Why did you try and stop her?

402
00:21:48,241 --> 00:21:50,401
-Listen!
-(CREAKING)

403
00:21:53,601 --> 00:21:55,121
(PANTING)

404
00:21:57,681 --> 00:22:00,241
(STAMMERING) Police.
Call the police. Call...

405
00:22:05,041 --> 00:22:07,841
-(RUSTLING)
-(SCREAMS)

406
00:22:09,841 --> 00:22:11,441
(FELICITY SCREAMING)

407
00:22:14,321 --> 00:22:15,441
What's happened to her?

408
00:22:16,361 --> 00:22:17,361
What's going on?

409
00:22:18,961 --> 00:22:20,961
Do you think it's like she said?
A thing?

410
00:22:21,441 --> 00:22:22,881
Maybe.

411
00:22:23,681 --> 00:22:26,001
And so, is it out there now, or in here?

412
00:22:26,121 --> 00:22:28,081
-Or both.
-I'm scared.

413
00:22:28,201 --> 00:22:29,521
-Don't be.
-Why not?

414
00:22:29,641 --> 00:22:30,641
It doesn't help.

415
00:22:34,721 --> 00:22:36,401
(CREAKING)

416
00:22:36,521 --> 00:22:37,961
Who's there?

417
00:22:38,481 --> 00:22:40,321
(VIOLIN MUSIC PLAYING)

418
00:22:51,921 --> 00:22:52,921
(SHRIEKS)

419
00:22:53,281 --> 00:22:54,801
-BILL: God.
-Pavel!

420
00:23:03,921 --> 00:23:05,921
BILL: Pavel...

421
00:23:06,001 --> 00:23:07,721
SHIREEN: Do you think he can hear us?

422
00:23:10,441 --> 00:23:11,921
BILL: It'll be okay.

423
00:23:12,241 --> 00:23:13,801
Is this what happened to Paul?

424
00:23:14,321 --> 00:23:16,321
-Do we call an ambulance?
-There's no reception.

425
00:23:16,401 --> 00:23:18,321
Shireen, sort the record out.

426
00:23:18,481 --> 00:23:20,881
-(PAVEL WHIMPERING)
-Oh, no, no. Wait, wait, wait.

427
00:23:23,681 --> 00:23:25,201
Is it something to do with the music?

428
00:23:30,001 --> 00:23:31,681
Did someone do this to you?

429
00:23:34,121 --> 00:23:36,241
-I have no desire to intrude...
-(BOTH GASP)

430
00:23:36,321 --> 00:23:37,681
But I felt there was a problem.

431
00:23:37,841 --> 00:23:40,161
How did you get up here?
It's sealed shut.

432
00:23:40,241 --> 00:23:43,441
Music can be pleasant,
but a simple repetition like that,

433
00:23:43,521 --> 00:23:46,401
it's merely a distraction
from the inevitable.

434
00:23:46,481 --> 00:23:48,401
-Hope is its own form of cruelty.
-(MUSIC STOPS)

435
00:23:48,801 --> 00:23:50,441
Pavel! No, wait, put it back!

436
00:23:53,121 --> 00:23:54,801
(LOUD CREAKING)

437
00:23:55,601 --> 00:23:56,641
Oh, look.

438
00:23:58,401 --> 00:23:59,921
He's released.

439
00:24:01,601 --> 00:24:02,961
Mercy at last.

440
00:24:03,721 --> 00:24:05,361
Beautiful, isn't it?

441
00:24:06,321 --> 00:24:07,841
Nature contained.

442
00:24:08,841 --> 00:24:10,881
He's preserved in the walls,

443
00:24:10,961 --> 00:24:14,161
in the very fabric
of the building, forever.

444
00:24:14,281 --> 00:24:16,401
So, the house is eating people?

445
00:24:16,521 --> 00:24:19,081
We must all pay our dues.

446
00:24:19,441 --> 00:24:21,201
-But not you?
-Correct!

447
00:24:22,001 --> 00:24:23,441
I am the exception.

448
00:24:26,881 --> 00:24:28,841
For I am your landlord.

449
00:24:29,441 --> 00:24:30,801
(CREAKING, RUSTLING)

450
00:24:30,921 --> 00:24:33,161
You came here, you signed the contract.

451
00:24:34,561 --> 00:24:36,081
And now...

452
00:24:37,681 --> 00:24:41,001
-(TUNING FORK VIBRATES)
-It's time to pay.

453
00:24:43,841 --> 00:24:45,521
-(CREAKING INTENSIFIES)
-Go.

454
00:24:50,761 --> 00:24:52,521
What's that noise?

455
00:24:52,641 --> 00:24:55,121
That tower,
it was at the back of the building.

456
00:24:55,521 --> 00:24:58,121
Logically, the door should be
at the end of this corridor.

457
00:25:00,321 --> 00:25:01,321
Look for a way in.

458
00:25:03,241 --> 00:25:05,201
Indiana Jones, come on.

459
00:25:09,681 --> 00:25:11,121
Yes, the tower.

460
00:25:14,961 --> 00:25:18,001
What if something has got into the wood?

461
00:25:18,481 --> 00:25:20,241
Into the laths, behind the plaster,

462
00:25:20,361 --> 00:25:23,601
into the very fabric of the house.

463
00:25:26,801 --> 00:25:27,921
Wood nymphs.

464
00:25:29,161 --> 00:25:30,321
Tree spirits.

465
00:25:31,561 --> 00:25:32,561
Dryads.

466
00:25:34,081 --> 00:25:35,081
Anything's possible.

467
00:25:40,041 --> 00:25:41,761
Doctor, what are you doing?

468
00:25:41,961 --> 00:25:44,241
We need to get out, call the police.

469
00:25:45,201 --> 00:25:46,961
-Who's there?
-(CREAKING)

470
00:25:47,081 --> 00:25:48,961
Doctor, you're provoking it.

471
00:25:49,041 --> 00:25:50,161
-(CREAKING INTENSIFIES)
-It's getting louder.

472
00:25:50,321 --> 00:25:52,001
Wake up! Wake up! Out you come!

473
00:25:56,881 --> 00:25:58,641
-Oh!
-(SHUDDERS)

474
00:25:58,721 --> 00:26:00,321
I was expecting something
quite different.

475
00:26:00,401 --> 00:26:02,481
You know, like a gaseous creature
or microscopic...

476
00:26:02,601 --> 00:26:03,841
Did you see it move through the wood?

477
00:26:04,081 --> 00:26:07,121
Interacting at a cellular level.
This must be alien.

478
00:26:07,241 --> 00:26:09,361
Got to be alien.
What are you doing here?

479
00:26:09,481 --> 00:26:10,561
On your holidays?

480
00:26:10,641 --> 00:26:12,201
-Harry, get a matchbox.
-A matchbox?

481
00:26:12,281 --> 00:26:13,961
All right, a shoe box...
Don't let it get away!

482
00:26:14,401 --> 00:26:15,841
What do you mean "alien"?

483
00:26:15,921 --> 00:26:19,361
-Oh, little one!
-Doctor...

484
00:26:19,441 --> 00:26:21,681
Oh, it can move fast.
Come on, where's that box?

485
00:26:21,801 --> 00:26:23,361
-Doctor!
-What?

486
00:26:26,001 --> 00:26:27,281
DOCTOR: Ah!

487
00:26:28,241 --> 00:26:32,401
Now, this starts to make sense.
Yes, dryads, indeed.

488
00:26:32,721 --> 00:26:33,761
We need to get out.

489
00:26:38,001 --> 00:26:39,041
We can't.

490
00:26:39,281 --> 00:26:40,641
Hey, in here!

491
00:26:43,441 --> 00:26:45,281
What's the point
of hiding in a cupboard?

492
00:26:46,001 --> 00:26:47,401
DOCTOR: It's not a cupboard.

493
00:26:56,561 --> 00:26:57,921
What are they?

494
00:26:58,001 --> 00:26:59,041
Look like insects,

495
00:26:59,121 --> 00:27:01,521
but you're saying
they can shut doors, trap us.

496
00:27:02,921 --> 00:27:06,801
They're not just in the wood.
They're becoming the wood itself.

497
00:27:06,881 --> 00:27:08,561
Total infestation.

498
00:27:08,721 --> 00:27:10,161
Infestation of the dryads.

499
00:27:10,281 --> 00:27:12,641
You're talking like
you've seen things like this before.

500
00:27:12,721 --> 00:27:15,921
-No, actually.
-You said they were alien.

501
00:27:16,041 --> 00:27:18,881
Well, they could be
native to this planet,

502
00:27:18,961 --> 00:27:20,401
but I've never seen them before.
Have you?

503
00:27:20,481 --> 00:27:22,641
And that's what they're called?
"Dryads"?

504
00:27:22,721 --> 00:27:24,841
Well, that's what I'm calling them, yes.

505
00:27:24,921 --> 00:27:25,921
You've gone crazy.

506
00:27:26,001 --> 00:27:28,121
Well, I can't just call them
lice, can I?

507
00:27:32,321 --> 00:27:33,961
(THUNDER RUMBLES)

508
00:27:53,201 --> 00:27:55,081
-(MUSIC BOX PLAYING)
-(GASPS)

509
00:27:56,881 --> 00:27:57,881
(MUSIC STOPS)

510
00:27:58,481 --> 00:28:00,521
-(CREAKING)
-(GASPS)

511
00:28:01,521 --> 00:28:03,241
(WHISPERS) There's something
behind there.

512
00:28:03,881 --> 00:28:05,321
WOMAN: Father?

513
00:28:05,841 --> 00:28:07,241
Is that you?

514
00:28:21,201 --> 00:28:23,241
Maybe it belonged to a family
that used to live here?

515
00:28:25,361 --> 00:28:27,601
Harry, there's six boxes.

516
00:28:30,481 --> 00:28:33,041
Tenancy agreement. Same as ours.

517
00:28:35,041 --> 00:28:36,241
Six signatures.

518
00:28:37,121 --> 00:28:39,921
Jake Christie, Annie Wren,
Jonathan Frost.

519
00:28:40,481 --> 00:28:43,921
-What's the date?
-Er, 1997.

520
00:28:44,681 --> 00:28:47,121
Sarah Tiller, Mark Hopethorne,
Carl Richards.

521
00:28:47,761 --> 00:28:51,041
They move in, relax...

522
00:28:52,681 --> 00:28:54,241
Go to their rooms.

523
00:28:56,081 --> 00:28:57,361
Then panic.

524
00:28:59,921 --> 00:29:00,961
Infestation.

525
00:29:05,441 --> 00:29:06,441
Doctor.

526
00:29:16,201 --> 00:29:17,441
1977.

527
00:29:19,761 --> 00:29:22,161
1957. Every 20 years.

528
00:29:22,241 --> 00:29:23,841
-(CREAKING)
-(GASPS)

529
00:29:24,401 --> 00:29:25,441
There's something coming.

530
00:29:26,321 --> 00:29:27,441
Good.

531
00:29:34,281 --> 00:29:35,281
Christie.

532
00:29:35,601 --> 00:29:40,081
Wren, Frost, Tiller,
Hopethorne, Richards...

533
00:29:40,521 --> 00:29:43,201
Fine young men and women.

534
00:29:43,281 --> 00:29:44,881
As were all the others.

535
00:29:47,841 --> 00:29:50,441
-Where are they?
-In the house.

536
00:29:50,641 --> 00:29:53,281
What? Where? We haven't seen 'em.

537
00:29:53,361 --> 00:29:55,681
He means, they're in the house.

538
00:29:57,601 --> 00:29:58,601
The wood, Harry.

539
00:29:59,921 --> 00:30:02,321
Don't think I haven't considered
the consequences, Doctor.

540
00:30:02,441 --> 00:30:03,521
So, why do it?

541
00:30:07,761 --> 00:30:09,321
My daughter was dying.

542
00:30:09,641 --> 00:30:11,081
What are you talking about?

543
00:30:11,281 --> 00:30:12,721
Nothing could be done.

544
00:30:15,121 --> 00:30:17,841
Until these creatures saved her.

545
00:30:20,521 --> 00:30:22,441
We'd do anything to protect them.

546
00:30:22,961 --> 00:30:24,601
Your daughter, she's here.
She's in the house, isn't she?

547
00:30:25,521 --> 00:30:26,961
Indeed.

548
00:30:27,841 --> 00:30:29,521
And she must survive.

549
00:30:30,001 --> 00:30:31,281
Well, we have to get out!

550
00:30:32,201 --> 00:30:33,681
- (EXCLAIMS)
-DOCTOR: Harry, stay with me!

551
00:30:33,801 --> 00:30:34,801
Come back, Harry!

552
00:30:35,121 --> 00:30:36,161
Come back!

553
00:30:39,681 --> 00:30:40,841
Ah! Doctor!

554
00:30:41,681 --> 00:30:42,681
Get him out!

555
00:30:46,241 --> 00:30:48,521
-(TUNING FORK VIBRATES)
-(SCREAMING)

556
00:30:52,721 --> 00:30:54,161
God rest his soul.

557
00:30:54,601 --> 00:30:55,921
Bill! Is Bill all right?

558
00:30:57,641 --> 00:30:59,361
I'd be more concerned
for yourself, Doctor.

559
00:30:59,561 --> 00:31:02,321
Your advanced age
means you have less energy,

560
00:31:02,441 --> 00:31:04,161
less matter.

561
00:31:04,241 --> 00:31:06,241
But they will take what they can get.

562
00:31:07,201 --> 00:31:09,201
DOCTOR: The insects
are keeping your daughter alive.

563
00:31:09,681 --> 00:31:10,721
How does that work?

564
00:31:11,681 --> 00:31:14,641
Come on, call these off.
Maybe I could help.

565
00:31:14,961 --> 00:31:16,481
I'm a doctor.

566
00:31:18,321 --> 00:31:19,601
Er, are you okay?

567
00:31:20,641 --> 00:31:22,161
(WOMAN WHEEZING)

568
00:31:23,521 --> 00:31:26,961
WOMAN: I haven't had visitors
in such a long time.

569
00:31:29,321 --> 00:31:31,281
My name is Eliza.

570
00:31:32,521 --> 00:31:36,001
-I'm Bill. This is Shireen.
-Hey.

571
00:31:43,121 --> 00:31:45,001
I'm pleased to meet you.

572
00:31:45,201 --> 00:31:46,281
Bill...

573
00:31:46,481 --> 00:31:47,681
(WHEEZING)

574
00:31:52,201 --> 00:31:53,481
What?

575
00:31:53,841 --> 00:31:58,001
You've got something just... Just there.

576
00:32:00,361 --> 00:32:02,241
I'm a celebrity,
get me out of here, yeah?

577
00:32:02,481 --> 00:32:04,401
-(FLOORBOARD CREAKING)
-SHIREEN: Bill...

578
00:32:08,841 --> 00:32:10,001
Cockroaches.

579
00:32:10,081 --> 00:32:12,841
Had 'em on my gap year in Morocco.
No problem. Let's go.

580
00:32:13,121 --> 00:32:14,161
Shireen...

581
00:32:15,281 --> 00:32:18,601
SHIREEN: (GASPING) Oh, no... Oh, no!

582
00:32:18,961 --> 00:32:20,521
It's in my foot!

583
00:32:22,601 --> 00:32:24,001
-(SHIREEN SCREAMING)
-BILL: Shireen!

584
00:32:29,041 --> 00:32:31,081
(STAMMERING)
I don't understand. She's...

585
00:32:31,401 --> 00:32:34,321
It's upsetting you. I understand.

586
00:32:34,401 --> 00:32:37,121
But Father says we have to survive.

587
00:32:43,201 --> 00:32:45,361
Eliza, do not fear this man.

588
00:32:46,441 --> 00:32:48,881
He says he might be able
to make you well.

589
00:32:51,121 --> 00:32:52,321
Bill, how are you?

590
00:32:53,761 --> 00:32:57,321
Yeah... Yeah, I'm okay. Er, Shireen...

591
00:32:57,521 --> 00:32:59,081
-The lice.
-Yeah.

592
00:32:59,241 --> 00:33:00,241
Harry, too.

593
00:33:00,361 --> 00:33:01,601
Um, in brief, he's her dad.

594
00:33:01,681 --> 00:33:03,521
He's been keeping her alive with
the bugs for about 70 years.

595
00:33:03,601 --> 00:33:06,801
Your friends are the food.
I said that I could help.

596
00:33:10,561 --> 00:33:13,761
Now, you must be Eliza.
How are you feeling? Rotten?

597
00:33:14,281 --> 00:33:15,761
I am quite well.

598
00:33:16,001 --> 00:33:17,681
Administer your treatment, Doctor.

599
00:33:18,081 --> 00:33:19,601
Well, what's the medical history here?
What happened?

600
00:33:19,681 --> 00:33:23,121
-Eliza, you were very ill. Yes?
-Yes.

601
00:33:24,801 --> 00:33:28,841
The doctors had, um, given up on you.

602
00:33:30,121 --> 00:33:32,321
But then, one day,
your father brings you a present.

603
00:33:32,401 --> 00:33:34,321
Where did you find them?
What, on the roof? In the garden?

604
00:33:36,721 --> 00:33:39,881
You find the insects,
you bring them into the house,

605
00:33:40,001 --> 00:33:41,881
er, because you want
to show them to her.

606
00:33:41,961 --> 00:33:43,761
Presumably, just to...

607
00:33:43,881 --> 00:33:45,041
Just to amuse her.

608
00:33:47,401 --> 00:33:48,721
I mean,
you couldn't have known what they were.

609
00:33:48,841 --> 00:33:50,161
Can you help her or not?

610
00:33:50,321 --> 00:33:52,321
I am helping. This is me helping.

611
00:33:52,401 --> 00:33:55,881
How did you find out
their unique abilities?

612
00:33:56,081 --> 00:33:58,161
Did you bring them in here?
You brought them in here, right,

613
00:33:58,281 --> 00:33:59,761
but what activated them?

614
00:34:00,001 --> 00:34:01,681
You use a tuning fork now, but...

615
00:34:01,801 --> 00:34:04,241
Pavel had that record on of a violin...

616
00:34:04,321 --> 00:34:05,641
High-pitched sounds, yes.

617
00:34:11,521 --> 00:34:14,561
-(MUSIC BOX PLAYING)
-(CREAKING)

618
00:34:14,641 --> 00:34:16,041
DOCTOR: Soothes her to sleep.

619
00:34:17,681 --> 00:34:18,961
High-pitched sound.

620
00:34:20,081 --> 00:34:22,721
You leave your daughter
alone for the night,

621
00:34:22,801 --> 00:34:24,161
or so you believe.

622
00:34:24,961 --> 00:34:27,441
The music wakes them. They set to work.

623
00:34:28,841 --> 00:34:31,921
And in the morning,
you find her revitalised.

624
00:34:32,161 --> 00:34:33,921
Just... Slightly wooden.

625
00:34:36,001 --> 00:34:38,881
You realise there's a way
she can survive.

626
00:34:38,961 --> 00:34:40,081
Enough!

627
00:34:40,201 --> 00:34:42,161
Wait, Doctor, that doesn't make sense.

628
00:34:42,321 --> 00:34:43,441
(MUSIC STOPS)

629
00:34:45,201 --> 00:34:47,281
Can you not interrupt?
I'm doing my thing here.

630
00:34:47,401 --> 00:34:49,641
Why would he pick up insects
in the garden

631
00:34:49,721 --> 00:34:50,801
and bring them in
to see his ill daughter?

632
00:34:51,201 --> 00:34:53,041
-Everyone loves insects.
-I don't.

633
00:34:53,201 --> 00:34:54,601
They're fascinating.

634
00:34:54,801 --> 00:34:58,281
Okay... Secondly, he's not wood.

635
00:34:59,601 --> 00:35:01,801
-He's just like us.
-He's...

636
00:35:02,801 --> 00:35:04,561
-Yes.
-So, if he's her father,

637
00:35:05,601 --> 00:35:08,321
-and she was preserved 70 years ago...
-(SONIC SCREWDRIVER PULSATING)

638
00:35:10,601 --> 00:35:11,761
DOCTOR: You...

639
00:35:12,681 --> 00:35:14,081
No flies on you, Bill.

640
00:35:15,441 --> 00:35:16,601
And no bugs in you.

641
00:35:17,761 --> 00:35:19,441
I do not understand.

642
00:35:19,521 --> 00:35:20,761
I forget, you see.

643
00:35:20,841 --> 00:35:23,761
Your human lifespan, it's...
It's not long, is it?

644
00:35:23,881 --> 00:35:25,841
Do not let them trouble you.

645
00:35:26,321 --> 00:35:28,201
What do you remember of the past, Eliza?

646
00:35:28,321 --> 00:35:31,361
My father...

647
00:35:32,681 --> 00:35:34,641
He knows what's best.

648
00:35:34,881 --> 00:35:36,601
Yes. The lice preserve the appearance

649
00:35:36,681 --> 00:35:38,241
and the voice,
but not so much the memories.

650
00:35:38,721 --> 00:35:40,881
-He's not your father, am I right?
-No!

651
00:35:41,841 --> 00:35:42,841
Stop talking!

652
00:35:43,241 --> 00:35:46,081
Father? What's the matter?

653
00:35:46,161 --> 00:35:47,681
I don't understand.

654
00:35:47,761 --> 00:35:50,321
Your father would have
had better things to do

655
00:35:50,721 --> 00:35:53,761
than playing with insects in the garden.

656
00:35:54,641 --> 00:35:56,641
-But he isn't your father.
-(ELIZA SOBBING)

657
00:35:56,721 --> 00:35:59,201
When you were ill,
he was sent out of the house

658
00:35:59,281 --> 00:36:00,481
by the doctors

659
00:36:00,641 --> 00:36:02,601
who were failing to save his mother.

660
00:36:02,721 --> 00:36:03,841
His...

661
00:36:05,041 --> 00:36:06,241
Mother?

662
00:36:09,601 --> 00:36:11,601
DOCTOR: Eliza, he's your son.

663
00:36:14,961 --> 00:36:16,841
Your loving son.

664
00:36:25,201 --> 00:36:26,401
(GASPS)

665
00:36:27,601 --> 00:36:28,681
My son?

666
00:36:33,161 --> 00:36:34,321
Forgive me.

667
00:36:37,001 --> 00:36:38,281
Forgive me.

668
00:36:47,361 --> 00:36:49,681
DOCTOR: When you saw
what the creatures had done,

669
00:36:49,761 --> 00:36:51,521
you understood, didn't you?

670
00:36:52,641 --> 00:36:54,281
The lice could keep your mother alive,

671
00:36:55,281 --> 00:36:59,841
if you protected them,
tamed them, fed them.

672
00:37:01,201 --> 00:37:03,601
If you could save the one
who brought you into this world,

673
00:37:03,681 --> 00:37:04,841
wouldn't you?

674
00:37:09,161 --> 00:37:11,121
Your silence is a confirmation.

675
00:37:13,921 --> 00:37:18,001
I did what you told me
because I thought you knew best.

676
00:37:19,601 --> 00:37:22,161
But I... I am your mother.

677
00:37:22,641 --> 00:37:24,481
-(SOBBING)
-And you...

678
00:37:27,401 --> 00:37:30,001
(SOBBING)
All these children you've taken...

679
00:37:30,641 --> 00:37:34,801
You told me it was necessary,
that we had no choice.

680
00:37:34,881 --> 00:37:38,081
That's right, it was.
It meant we could stay together.

681
00:37:38,161 --> 00:37:40,681
Don't you understand? We were happy.

682
00:37:41,681 --> 00:37:44,561
I kept our lives a secret,

683
00:37:44,881 --> 00:37:48,201
and a secret we must remain.

684
00:37:53,001 --> 00:37:55,361
(SNIFFLES) You have brought her
nothing but misery.

685
00:37:55,561 --> 00:37:56,961
And confusion!

686
00:37:58,001 --> 00:38:00,681
You will be taken. Like the others!

687
00:38:02,481 --> 00:38:04,321
(TUNING FORK VIBRATES)

688
00:38:07,121 --> 00:38:09,681
Okay... Now's the time for the plan.

689
00:38:09,841 --> 00:38:12,241
That was it, no plan.
Info dump then busk.

690
00:38:12,521 --> 00:38:13,521
Well, start busking.

691
00:38:13,681 --> 00:38:16,481
Eliza, people have died
and will continue to die

692
00:38:16,561 --> 00:38:18,481
unless you stop all this right now.

693
00:38:18,561 --> 00:38:19,921
How can I stop it?

694
00:38:20,041 --> 00:38:22,921
You're the parent. You're in charge!

695
00:38:31,721 --> 00:38:32,841
That's it.

696
00:38:36,041 --> 00:38:38,561
Do what I say! I control you!

697
00:38:40,241 --> 00:38:41,361
No.

698
00:38:42,801 --> 00:38:43,841
It's me.

699
00:38:45,601 --> 00:38:46,921
I control them.

700
00:38:48,081 --> 00:38:49,961
Eliza, finish them now.

701
00:38:50,441 --> 00:38:51,721
Take them or you'll die!

702
00:38:52,081 --> 00:38:53,521
They'll destroy you!

703
00:38:53,961 --> 00:38:56,561
What's the point of surviving
if you never see anyone,

704
00:38:56,641 --> 00:38:58,561
if you hide yourself
away from the world?

705
00:38:59,121 --> 00:39:00,641
When did you last open the shutters?

706
00:39:07,521 --> 00:39:09,521
(FIREWORKS EXPLODING)

707
00:39:12,681 --> 00:39:14,881
It's the freshers' party in the park.

708
00:39:14,961 --> 00:39:16,161
Exactly.

709
00:39:16,241 --> 00:39:19,121
New friends, fireworks.
That's what life should be.

710
00:39:21,161 --> 00:39:22,441
I remember.

711
00:39:24,721 --> 00:39:26,001
My son.

712
00:39:27,761 --> 00:39:30,081
Leave my side at last.

713
00:39:31,841 --> 00:39:33,601
Go and see the world.

714
00:39:33,681 --> 00:39:36,081
No. I don't want to.

715
00:39:36,721 --> 00:39:38,801
If you won't finish them,

716
00:39:41,281 --> 00:39:42,481
I will!

717
00:39:47,441 --> 00:39:48,881
My little boy.

718
00:39:49,201 --> 00:39:50,641
This has to end.

719
00:39:51,121 --> 00:39:55,121
No, we mustn't end.
We have to destroy them.

720
00:39:55,281 --> 00:39:56,881
It's our time.

721
00:40:00,521 --> 00:40:02,641
No, I... I don't want to.

722
00:40:05,801 --> 00:40:07,761
(SOBBING) No. No.

723
00:40:10,161 --> 00:40:11,201
Thank you.

724
00:40:14,481 --> 00:40:15,601
(GASPS)

725
00:40:19,601 --> 00:40:21,681
-(CREAKING)
-We've got to get out of here.

726
00:40:22,921 --> 00:40:24,001
Is that...

727
00:40:24,081 --> 00:40:26,321
DOCTOR: Yes, your friend.
She's restoring them.

728
00:40:28,041 --> 00:40:29,281
(GRUNTING)

729
00:40:32,401 --> 00:40:35,521
-I thought you were gone.
-Are you okay?

730
00:40:35,601 --> 00:40:37,201
Me? Yeah, I'm fine.

731
00:40:37,281 --> 00:40:38,281
(CREAKING)

732
00:40:38,561 --> 00:40:40,081
-What about the others?
-Come on!

733
00:40:42,601 --> 00:40:43,761
(CREAKING GROWS LOUDER)

734
00:40:47,761 --> 00:40:49,281
We need to get out! Now!

735
00:40:56,881 --> 00:40:58,641
Wrong way! Wrong way! Wrong way!

736
00:41:04,521 --> 00:41:06,321
Down goes the deposit.

737
00:41:06,401 --> 00:41:08,241
Oh, man, that's our house.

738
00:41:09,361 --> 00:41:10,481
Gone.

739
00:41:13,361 --> 00:41:15,841
Right, you lot.
Back to the estate agent's.

740
00:41:18,761 --> 00:41:20,161
Better luck next time.

741
00:41:27,201 --> 00:41:29,121
NARDOLE: Well, here he comes.

742
00:41:29,201 --> 00:41:31,121
Are you being cheerful?
I'm against cheerful.

743
00:41:31,281 --> 00:41:33,521
Bill told me you went on
a little adventure.

744
00:41:34,241 --> 00:41:36,161
-You see?
-I see what?

745
00:41:36,241 --> 00:41:40,361
Well, you don't have to go
to outer space to find monsters.

746
00:41:40,681 --> 00:41:43,361
There's plenty of things want
to kill you right here on Earth.

747
00:41:43,441 --> 00:41:44,641
Result.

748
00:41:45,521 --> 00:41:48,561
Hmm. Actually, I'm not that hungry.

749
00:41:48,721 --> 00:41:51,041
-Well, I am.
-Obviously.

750
00:41:52,801 --> 00:41:54,641
Okay, you can take
the rest of the night off.

751
00:41:54,801 --> 00:41:56,401
Go on, go and do whatever it is you do.

752
00:41:56,641 --> 00:41:59,121
Actually, what do you do?
No. Never tell me that.

753
00:41:59,401 --> 00:42:01,361
Yeah, I just want
to have a look at this.

754
00:42:01,481 --> 00:42:04,401
Our friend inside's
been a little restive lately.

755
00:42:04,481 --> 00:42:06,081
Erm, I can sort that out.

756
00:42:06,161 --> 00:42:09,001
-No, it's all right. I don't mind.
-Good night, Nardole.

757
00:42:12,401 --> 00:42:14,721
Right. Good night, sir.

758
00:42:15,761 --> 00:42:17,361
See you in the morning.

759
00:42:17,481 --> 00:42:19,601
(PIANO MUSIC PLAYING)

760
00:42:24,561 --> 00:42:25,561
A piano?

761
00:42:26,401 --> 00:42:28,201
You've put a piano in there. Why?

762
00:42:29,201 --> 00:42:30,281
Good night.

763
00:42:31,521 --> 00:42:34,321
(SIGHS) You don't learn, do you, sir?

764
00:42:45,601 --> 00:42:49,041
Hey! Do you want dinner?
I've got Mexican.

765
00:42:49,281 --> 00:42:50,481
(MUSIC STOPS)

766
00:42:51,721 --> 00:42:52,961
Look...

767
00:42:53,521 --> 00:42:56,801
I know you miss it all,
but I'm stuck here, too, you know.

768
00:42:56,881 --> 00:42:58,481
We're both prisoners.

769
00:42:59,081 --> 00:43:00,481
So, what do you say? Dinner?

770
00:43:03,281 --> 00:43:05,161
And I've got a new story for you, too.

771
00:43:05,961 --> 00:43:08,721
There's a haunted house
and woodlice from space.

772
00:43:11,721 --> 00:43:13,681
And lots of young people get eaten.

773
00:43:14,481 --> 00:43:16,721
(PIANO MUSIC PLAYING)

774
00:43:22,001 --> 00:43:23,121
I'm coming in.

775
00:43:25,361 --> 00:43:26,361
(MUSIC STOPS)

776
00:43:30,001 --> 00:43:31,081
DOCTOR: Mining station. Chasm.

777
00:43:31,601 --> 00:43:33,041
A forge. Crew of 40.

778
00:43:33,521 --> 00:43:34,641
Hello?

779
00:43:34,881 --> 00:43:36,041
Four survivors.

780
00:43:37,601 --> 00:43:38,961
One distress call.

781
00:43:39,441 --> 00:43:40,721
They were killed by their own suits.

782
00:43:41,641 --> 00:43:44,721
NARDOLE:. That means there's 36 corpses
walking about this station.

783
00:43:45,121 --> 00:43:46,241
DOCTOR:
If we want to keep breathing,

784
00:43:46,321 --> 00:43:48,641
we have exactly one option.

785
00:43:48,801 --> 00:43:50,801
MAN: None of us
have more than 3,000 breaths left.

786
00:43:50,881 --> 00:43:51,921
Then stop wasting them.

787
00:43:58,801 --> 00:44:00,721
(THEME MUSIC PLAYING)

